\subsection{Resource Footprint Comparison}
Peak heap allocation of 13.8 KB in hybrid mode represents approximately 2.65\% of the ESP32's 520 KB internal SRAM. The ML-KEM-512 secret key buffer alone (1,632 bytes) accounts for a significant portion of this memory. By comparison, the baseline mbedTLS 1.3 stack consumed a peak of 9.16 KB of dynamic heap overhead specifically for the cryptographic handshake state. This reveals a critical trade-off: our protocol requires 13.8 KB, compared to 9.16 KB for the TLS heap baseline, a 4.64 KB increase to accommodate lattice key structures. However, it simultaneously reduces cryptographic latency by bypassing conventional TLS state machines. The 1,713-byte combined handshake payload fits comfortably within standard TCP segments, ensuring reliable delivery over 802.11n Wi-Fi without significant MTU fragmentation delays.

